article.description:
Mwadi Mabika scored 26 points, and the Los
Angeles Sparks overcame the absence of injured all-star Lisa Leslie
to defeat the Phoenix Mercury 80-77 in double overtime Tuesday
night.

article.headline: Mabika, Sparks hand Mercury another loss
article.linkText: Without Leslie, Sparks hold off Mercury
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Sparks learned that life
without Lisa Leslie can be quite challenging.

With the MVP sidelined for the first of at least three games,
the Sparks needed two overtimes to defeat the last-place Phoenix
Mercury, 80-77 Tuesday night.

"Any time you lose one of your soldiers, it's a big impact, but
I think last year prepared us for what we're facing now," Los
Angeles guard Tamecka Dixon said. "Lisa, I, Mwadi (Mabika) spent a
couple of games out, and we were able to rally around each other
and pull out the victories.

Mwadi Mabika scored 26 points for the Western Conference-leading
Sparks (16-3), before fouling out with 4.4 seconds left.

Rookie Plenette Pierson had a season-high 26 points for Phoenix
(3-15), which has lost eight of nine.

Rhonda Mapp, starting at center in place of Leslie, made a
four-footer to send the game into overtime. Leslie was placed on
the injured reserve list for the first time in her career earlier
Tuesday.

Leslie will have to miss a minimum of three games under league
rules. She bruised a bone in her right knee when she collided with
Detroit's Swin Cash in Saturday's All-Star game.

Tamecka Dixon added 18 points for Los Angeles, a winner of four
straight games and seven of eight.

The Mercury did not score in the second overtime until Kayte
Christensen converted the second of two free throws with 1:55
remaining, cutting the deficit to 74-69.

"We play hard, we play well for the majority of the game, and
we just haven't finished the games well enough at the end, but
we're a step closer," Mercury coach John Shumate said. "We just
have to continue to work."

Nikki Teasley's two free throws with 27.1 seconds left gave the
Sparks a 78-75 lead. After Pierson and Nicky McCrimmon exchanged
layups, Iziane Castro Marques missed a 3-point shot for Phoenix as
the buzzer sounded.

The Sparks trailed 28-27 at halftime but outscored Phoenix 11-1
to open the second half, taking a 38-29 lead with 16:36 to play.

Leslie received a standing ovation before the game as she walked
with the aid of crutches to the bench.

The Sparks missed all 10 of their 3-point shots, the first time
they have not made a 3-pointer since July 11, 1999.
